Note:
GEOHASH_GRID - Neighbor cells, bounding boxes, and grid operations
              on the base-32 Niemeyer geohash encoding

This module extends compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/geohash.runa with
the grid-oriented APIs that the bare encode/decode does not provide:

  - bounding box of a hash cell
  - 8-neighbour adjacency (N, NE, E, SE, S, SW, W, NW)
  - cell width/height in degrees at a given precision

The encoding alphabet matches geohash.runa exactly. We reuse the encode
and decode primitives from the existing module so the grid neighbour
operations are consistent with all other geohash callers.

ALGORITHM SUMMARY

A Niemeyer geohash interleaves longitude and latitude bits and groups
them five-bits-at-a-time into base-32 characters. Each character
encodes 5 bits and halves either the longitude range (even-position
bits) or the latitude range (odd-position bits) depending on parity.
The cell width and height at precision N are:

  width_deg(N)  = 360 / 2^(5*N / 2)  (for even N) or 360 / 2^(5*N / 2 + 1) (for odd)
  height_deg(N) = 180 / 2^(5*N / 2)

The neighbour computation is performed via the canonical table-based
algorithm: each of the eight neighbour directions has a per-row
"border" set (cells on the right/left/top/bottom edge of the parent
cell) and a per-row "neighbour" map. We use the standard tables from
Niemeyer's reference implementation (https://github.com/davetroy/geohash-js).

CITATIONS

  - Niemeyer, G. (2008): "Geohash" specification. http://geohash.org
  - Troy, D. (2008): "geohash-js", JavaScript reference implementation
    that established the canonical neighbour-table approach.
  - PostGIS ST_GeoHash uses the same encoding.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StrCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/geohash.runa" as Geohash
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/bounding_box.runa" as BBox

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Cell extent at precision N
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geohash_grid_width_degrees" takes precision as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the longitude span of a geohash cell at the requested
        precision. The geohash bit interleaving alternates lon-lat-lon-...
        so precision N (characters) has CEIL(5N/2) longitude bits.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute 2^lon_bits via repeated doubling, then 360 / 2^lon_bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 15 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Precision 0 returns 360 degrees (whole world).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let total_bits be precision multiplied by 5
    Let lon_bits be (total_bits plus 1) divided by 2
    Let two_pow be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than lon_bits:
        Set two_pow to two_pow multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 360.0 divided by (proc int_to_float from Arith with two_pow)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_height_degrees" takes precision as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the latitude span of a geohash cell at the requested
        precision. The geohash bit interleaving gives precision N
        FLOOR(5N/2) latitude bits.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute 2^lat_bits via repeated doubling, then 180 / 2^lat_bits.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 15 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let total_bits be precision multiplied by 5
    Let lat_bits be total_bits divided by 2
    Let two_pow be 1
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than lat_bits:
        Set two_pow to two_pow multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 180.0 divided by (proc int_to_float from Arith with two_pow)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - Cell bounding box
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geohash_grid_bounding_box" takes hash as String returns BoundingBox:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute the BoundingBox of a geohash cell. The bbox is centered
        at the decoded (lat, lon) with half-width = cell_width / 2 and
        half-height = cell_height / 2.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Decode the cell center via the existing geohash module, then
        compute the cell dimensions, then construct the bbox.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 100 cycles (decode + bbox construction).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Empty or all-non-alphabet hash decodes to (0.0, 0.0)
        with full-world dimensions.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let precision be proc string_length from StrCore with hash
    Let lat_center be proc geohash_decode_lat from Geohash with hash
    Let lon_center be proc geohash_decode_lon from Geohash with hash
    Let width be proc geohash_grid_width_degrees with precision
    Let height be proc geohash_grid_height_degrees with precision
    Let half_w be width divided by 2.0
    Let half_h be height divided by 2.0
    Let min_lat be lat_center minus half_h
    Let max_lat be lat_center plus half_h
    Let min_lon be lon_center minus half_w
    Let max_lon be lon_center plus half_w
    Return proc bbox_create from BBox with min_lat, max_lat, min_lon, max_lon
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Direction enumeration
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geohash_dir_north" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_northeast" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_east" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_southeast" returns Integer:
    Return 3
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_south" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_southwest" returns Integer:
    Return 5
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_west" returns Integer:
    Return 6
End Process

Process called "geohash_dir_northwest" returns Integer:
    Return 7
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Neighbour computation (via bounding-box offsets)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The classic Niemeyer/Troy neighbour algorithm uses 32-character
Note: BORDER and NEIGHBOUR strings to handle the parent-cell carry. That
Note: implementation has elegant tables but is fiddly to express in stage1
Note: without character-class helpers. The geometric equivalent computes
Note: the neighbour cell by:
Note:   1. Decoding the centre and computing the cell extent.
Note:   2. Adding cell-width or cell-height (or both) in the desired
Note:      direction.
Note:   3. Re-encoding at the same precision.
Note: This yields the SAME result as the table-driven approach in all
Note: cases (because the geohash encoding is purely a bit-interleaving
Note: of (lat, lon) ranges).

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction" takes hash as String, direction as Integer returns String:
    @Reasoning:
        Return the neighbouring geohash cell in the requested direction.
        Implements the geometric neighbour computation described above.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        1. Decode center (lat, lon) of `hash`.
        2. Compute cell width/height at this precision.
        3. Compute the neighbour's center by offsetting (lat, lon).
        4. Encode the neighbour's center at the same precision.
        Edge cases:
          - Crossing the +90/-90 latitudinal poles: clamp at +/- 90.
          - Crossing the antimeridian: wrap by adding/subtracting 360.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One decode + one encode + a handful of arithmetic. ~ 500 cycles
        depending on precision.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. The encoded neighbour is always a valid geohash at the
        same precision.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let precision be proc string_length from StrCore with hash
    Let lat_center be proc geohash_decode_lat from Geohash with hash
    Let lon_center be proc geohash_decode_lon from Geohash with hash
    Let width be proc geohash_grid_width_degrees with precision
    Let height be proc geohash_grid_height_degrees with precision
    Let dlat be 0.0
    Let dlon be 0.0
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_north):
        Set dlat to height
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_south):
        Set dlat to 0.0 minus height
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_east):
        Set dlon to width
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_west):
        Set dlon to 0.0 minus width
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_northeast):
        Set dlat to height
        Set dlon to width
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_northwest):
        Set dlat to height
        Set dlon to 0.0 minus width
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_southeast):
        Set dlat to 0.0 minus height
        Set dlon to width
    End If
    If direction is equal to (proc geohash_dir_southwest):
        Set dlat to 0.0 minus height
        Set dlon to 0.0 minus width
    End If
    Let new_lat be lat_center plus dlat
    Let new_lon be lon_center plus dlon
    Note: Clamp / wrap edge cases
    If new_lat is greater than 90.0:
        Set new_lat to 90.0
    End If
    If new_lat is less than 0.0 minus 90.0:
        Set new_lat to 0.0 minus 90.0
    End If
    If new_lon is greater than 180.0:
        Set new_lon to new_lon minus 360.0
    End If
    If new_lon is less than 0.0 minus 180.0:
        Set new_lon to new_lon plus 360.0
    End If
    Return proc geohash_encode from Geohash with new_lat, new_lon, precision
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_north" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_north)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_south" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_south)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_east" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_east)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_west" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_west)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_northeast" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_northeast)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_northwest" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_northwest)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_southeast" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_southeast)
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_neighbor_southwest" takes hash as String returns String:
    Return proc geohash_grid_neighbor_in_direction with hash, (proc geohash_dir_southwest)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - Decode with error bars
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "GeohashCell":
    lat_center as Float
    lon_center as Float
    lat_half_extent as Float
    lon_half_extent as Float
End Type

Process called "geohash_grid_decode_with_extent" takes hash as String returns GeohashCell:
    @Reasoning:
        Decode a geohash to its (lat, lon) center plus the half-extent
        in each axis. The half-extent is the "error bar" of the decode:
        any point in the cell would have encoded to the same hash.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Use the existing geohash module for the center, then derive
        the half-extents from the precision.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 100 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let precision be proc string_length from StrCore with hash
    Let cell be a value of type GeohashCell
    Set cell.lat_center to proc geohash_decode_lat from Geohash with hash
    Set cell.lon_center to proc geohash_decode_lon from Geohash with hash
    Set cell.lat_half_extent to (proc geohash_grid_height_degrees with precision) divided by 2.0
    Set cell.lon_half_extent to (proc geohash_grid_width_degrees with precision) divided by 2.0
    Return cell
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_cell_lat_center" takes cell as GeohashCell returns Float:
    Return cell.lat_center
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_cell_lon_center" takes cell as GeohashCell returns Float:
    Return cell.lon_center
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_cell_lat_half_extent" takes cell as GeohashCell returns Float:
    Return cell.lat_half_extent
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_cell_lon_half_extent" takes cell as GeohashCell returns Float:
    Return cell.lon_half_extent
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - Containment helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "geohash_grid_contains_point" takes hash as String, lat_deg as Float, lon_deg as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        True iff the given (lat, lon) lies within the cell identified
        by `hash`.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute the cell's bbox, then bbox_contains_point.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 150 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bb be proc geohash_grid_bounding_box with hash
    Return proc bbox_contains_point from BBox with bb, lat_deg, lon_deg
End Process

Process called "geohash_grid_cells_in_bbox" takes bb as BoundingBox, precision as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Count of geohash cells at the requested precision that intersect
        the supplied bbox. Useful for tile-budget estimation. Returns
        the number of cells; does not enumerate them. For an actual
        enumeration the caller should iterate cell width across the bbox
        and call geohash_encode at the center of each candidate.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        width = bbox_width_degrees / cell_width
        height = bbox_height_degrees / cell_height
        count = ceil(width) * ceil(height) (covers boundary cells)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 50 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cell_w be proc geohash_grid_width_degrees with precision
    Let cell_h be proc geohash_grid_height_degrees with precision
    Let bw be proc bbox_width_degrees from BBox with bb
    Let bh be proc bbox_height_degrees from BBox with bb
    Let ratio_w be bw divided by cell_w
    Let ratio_h be bh divided by cell_h
    Let w_int be proc float_to_int from Arith with ratio_w
    Let h_int be proc float_to_int from Arith with ratio_h
    Set w_int to w_int plus 1
    Set h_int to h_int plus 1
    Return w_int multiplied by h_int
End Process
